The standard approach in .NET is to use `System.IO.Abstractions`:

1. **Install the NuGet package:**
   ```
   dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
   ```

2. **Inject `IFileSystem` instead of calling static methods directly:**
   ```csharp
   public class MyService
   {
       private readonly IFileSystem _fs;
       public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;

       public void Save(string path, string content)
           => _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, content);
   }
   ```

3. **In production**, register the real implementation:
   ```csharp
   services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
   ```

4. **In tests**, use the companion package `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`:
   ```csharp
   var fs = new MockFileSystem();
   var svc = new MyService(fs);
   svc.Save("/tmp/test.txt", "hello");
   Assert.Equal("hello", fs.File.ReadAllText("/tmp/test.txt"));
   ```

`IFileSystem` wraps `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, and more — so it covers all three calls you mentioned. This avoids hand-rolling your own interface and gives you a battle-tested in-memory file system for tests.
